                <!-- SEO Content Area -->
                <article class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md mt-8 prose">
                    <h2>Data Source and Methodology</h2>
                    <p><strong>Authoritative Source:</strong> Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB), "What should I know about mortgage interest rates?"
                    <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-should-i-know-about-mortgage-interest-rates-en-135/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">CFPB Official Guidance</a></p>
                    <p>All calculations use standard fixed-rate mortgage amortization formulas. The calculator implements the same formulas used by financial institutions and is based on CFPB consumer education materials.</p>

                    <h2>The Formula Explained</h2>
                    <div class="formula-box">
                        <p><strong>Monthly Payment:</strong></p>
                        <p>M = P × [r(1 + r)^n] / [(1 + r)^n - 1]</p>
                        <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>M = Monthly payment</li>
                            <li>P = Principal (loan amount)</li>
                            <li>r = Monthly interest rate (annual rate ÷ 12)</li>
                            <li>n = Total number of payments (years × 12)</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p><strong>Total Interest:</strong> (M × n) - P</p>
                    </div>

                    <h2>Key Differences: 15-Year vs 30-Year Mortgages</h2>
                    <h3>15-Year Mortgage Advantages</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Lower interest rates:</strong> Typically 0.5%-1% lower than 30-year rates</li>
                        <li><strong>Massive interest savings:</strong> Can save $100,000+ over the life of the loan</li>
                        <li><strong>Build equity faster:</strong> Own your home outright in half the time</li>
                        <li><strong>Forced savings:</strong> Higher payments create wealth through home equity</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>30-Year Mortgage Advantages</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Lower monthly payments:</strong> More affordable month-to-month</li>
                        <li><strong>Greater flexibility:</strong> Extra cash for other investments or expenses</li>
                        <li><strong>Easier qualification:</strong> Lower payment makes debt-to-income ratios better</li>
                        <li><strong>Inflation hedge:</strong> Fixed payments become cheaper in real terms over time</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h2>How to Choose: Decision Framework</h2>
                    <p><strong>Choose a 15-year mortgage if:</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>You can comfortably afford the higher monthly payment</li>
                        <li>You want to be debt-free faster</li>
                        <li>You're nearing retirement and want to eliminate housing costs</li>
                        <li>You prioritize minimizing interest costs</li>
                        <li>You have stable, high income</li>
                    </ol>

                    <p><strong>Choose a 30-year mortgage if:</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>You need lower monthly payments for budget flexibility</li>
                        <li>You can invest the payment difference at returns exceeding mortgage rate</li>
                        <li>You're a first-time homebuyer with limited cash reserves</li>
                        <li>You value having emergency funds and financial cushion</li>
                        <li>You plan to move before the loan matures</li>
                    </ol>

                    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>What is the typical interest rate difference between 15-year and 30-year mortgages?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">15-year mortgages typically have interest rates 0.5% to 1.0% lower than 30-year mortgages because lenders have less long-term risk. This lower rate, combined with the shorter term, results in substantial interest savings.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Can I pay off a 30-year mortgage early to match a 15-year schedule?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Yes, you can make extra principal payments on a 30-year mortgage to pay it off faster. However, you'll still pay the higher 30-year interest rate. Most mortgages have no prepayment penalty, but always confirm with your lender.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>How much can I save with a 15-year mortgage?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">On a $300,000 loan, you might save $150,000-$200,000 in interest with a 15-year mortgage compared to a 30-year. The exact savings depend on interest rates and loan amount.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Is it harder to qualify for a 15-year mortgage?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">Yes, because monthly payments are higher. Lenders use debt-to-income (DTI) ratios, and the higher 15-year payment may push you over acceptable DTI limits. You typically need stronger income to qualify.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>What if interest rates drop after I get a 15-year mortgage?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">You can refinance to a lower rate, though you'll pay closing costs. If rates drop significantly (typically 0.75%+), refinancing may save money even after fees.</p>
                    </details>
                    <details class="border-b py-2">
                        <summary>Should I get a 15-year mortgage if I'm young?</summary>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">It depends on your financial goals. Some young buyers prefer 30-year mortgages for flexibility to invest in retirement accounts or business ventures. Others prefer 15-year mortgages to build home equity and eliminate housing costs before retirement.</p>
                    </details>

                    <div class="mt-6 p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg border border-gray-200">
